#### Every lesson ends with a wrap-up, allowing students to reflect on key skills and concepts. 
</p></div>
</details>

### **Lesson Types**

<details style="background-color: #ececec; padding: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; border: 1px solid transparent; border-radius: 5px;">
    <summary style="font-size: 1.5em; font-weight: bold;">💻 Programming Lessons</summary>
<div style="margin-top: 20px; margin-left: 20px; margin-right: 20px;">
    <p>

#### Programming lessons teach new concepts and skills through computer-based activities. Students often work in groups or as a class, with teachers actively facilitating sense-making and formative assessments. 
</p></div>
</details>

<details style="background-color: #ececec; padding: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; border: 1px solid transparent; border-radius: 5px;">
    <summary style="font-size: 1.5em; font-weight: bold;">✍🏽 Non-Programming Lessons</summary>
<div style="margin-top: 20px; margin-left: 20px; margin-right: 20px;">
    <p>


#### Non-programming lessons emphasize process skills and computing concepts, mostly through offline activities guided by an activity sheet. They include opportunities for group collaboration, discussion, and individual reflection, with some online components.
</p></div>
</details>

<details style="background-color: #ececec; padding: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; border: 1px solid transparent; border-radius: 5px;">
    <summary style="font-size: 1.5em; font-weight: bold;">👩‍💻 Project Lessons</summary>
<div style="margin-top: 20px; margin-left: 20px; margin-right: 20px;">
    <p>


#### ***Mini-projects*** let students apply their learning in an open-ended way, practicing new skills. These flexible projects appear throughout the unit and can be adjusted based on available class time.

#### ***Projects*** are multi-day, open-ended lessons at the end of each unit, where students use learned skills to plan, create, and reflect.
</p></div>
</details>


